If the base type is partially instantiated we use its canonical form:

class A<T, U> {}

class B<T> : A<string, T> {}

In this case we will have:

class B<System.__Canon> : A<System.__Canon, System.__Canon>

This patch fixes https://github.com/dotnet/corert/issues/6682

Following sample compiles incorrectly:
```cs
using System;

namespace Hello
{
    internal class Program
    {
        class A<T, U>
        {

        }

        class C<T>
        {

        }

        class B<T> : A<string, C<T>>
        {

        }

        private static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            var b = new B<string>();
            Console.WriteLine("b = " + b);
        }
    }
}
```
`B<System.__Canon>` doesn't inherit `A`:
```
namespace Hello { namespace Hello { class Program_B_1_A__System___Canon_V_ {
                public:
                        static MethodTable * __getMethodTable();
                        static void _ctor(::Hello::Hello::Program_B_1_A__System___Canon_V_*);
                        static void unbox__ctor(::Hello::Hello::Program_B_1_A__System___Canon_V_*);
};
};};
```

One of the problems is that `B<System.__Canon>` is emitted before `A<System.__Canon, System.__Canon>`. So the check `_emittedTypes.Contains(nodeType.BaseType)` in `CppWriter.OutputTypeNode` returns false. Are there any guarantees that base type is emitted before type itself?

Thank you!

Add cast in `ImportStoreField` to handle cases like following:
```cs
class A<T, U>
{
    public T t;
    public U u;
}

class B<T> : A<string, T>>
{
    public B() { t = "123" }
}
```
As `A<System.__Canon, System.__Canon>` is used as base for `B<System.__Canon>` `t` has `System.__Canon` type in B's ctor and we need to cast it to `string`.

