This borrows the implementation strategy for these from CoreRT. It makes it both simpler (fewer types and lines of code) and faster in some cases since we always use the exact right underlying type.

E.g. The following micro-benchmark is 25% faster with this change:

```
enum MyEnum : byte { x, y };

var comparer = Comparer<MyEnum>.Default;

for (int i = 0; i < 100000000; i++)
{
    comparer.Compare(MyEnum.x, MyEnum.y);
    comparer.Compare(MyEnum.y, MyEnum.x);
}
```

[Path.DirectorySeparatorChar](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.io.path.directoryseparatorchar?view=netcore-2.1) and [Path.AltDirectorySeparatorChar](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.io.path.altdirectoryseparatorchar?view=netcore-2.1) are both the '/' char in Ubuntu.

I think this is causing that `Path.GetFileName()`, running under Ubuntu, if supplied with an argument that is a Windows path (like `C:\temp\file.txt`) will not return the correct file name.

It is written in the [Path.GetFileName() documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.io.path.getfilename?view=netcore-2.1)  that:

> The separator characters used to determine the start of the file name are DirectorySeparatorChar and AltDirectorySeparatorChar.

If these fields were holding the chars '/' and '\\' then `Path.GetFileName()` would probably get the correct file name, from a windows path, while running in a Ubuntu machine. But since they are the same, the method, running under Ubuntu, returns the full windows path.

Test code:

```csharp
using System;

namespace myApp
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(System.IO.Path.AltDirectorySeparatorChar);
            Console.WriteLine(System.IO.Path.DirectorySeparatorChar);
            Console.WriteLine(System.IO.Path.GetFileName(@"C:\temp\img.jpg"));
            Console.WriteLine(System.IO.Path.GetFileName("/tmp/img.jpg"));
        }
    }
}
```

Output of `dotnet run`:

```
/
/
C:\temp\img.jpg
img.jpg
```

